THE Egyptians, who would deem it sacrilege to taste an onion or a leek, have in our enlightened times been guilty of barbarity which equals that of the nionsters of fable (1—32). A festival at Ombi was lateiy iuterrupted by the Tentyrites: one of whom, after his party had been put to flight, was over- taken, torn in pieces and devoured (33—92). Other nations are said to have fed on the flesh of man, but only when driven to it by famine: rage and hate niove‘the Egyptians to crimes which others only commit in the madness of despair (93—131). Man is made for society and sympathy3 yet man has been known to do what brute beasts will not do, to prey upon his own kind (131—174).
